T1  - An option model approach to firm liquidity management
AU  - Levasseur, Michel G.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 1
IS  - 1
SP  - 13
EP  - 28
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/06/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(77)90016-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426677900164
AB  - With an awareness of the famous Keynesian motives of demand for liquidity, we look at the cases of speculative and precautionary demand at the level of an individual firm. In countries like France, having alternative periods of large liquidity and credit squeeze, the firm's demand for liquidity is not only a transaction demand, but is also influenced by financial imperatives. The problem is to evaluate theoretically the amount of this demand and to elucidate the explicative variables. A valuation formula is derived from a comparison between a liquidity investment and a common stock call option. At this point, the now well-known theory of option pricing is used to obtain an explicit form of this valuation formula.
ER  - 
